segments.text: But either way, our movement absolutely cannot simply just afford to put our faith in City Hall and wait for them to act.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: Our movement needs to immediately prepare to file a grassroots ballot initiative.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: And our goal should be to file that ballot initiative in February.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: So our timeline is steep.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: We need to urgently begin to collect signatures to get it on the November ballot where we can expect historically high voter turnout in a presidential election year.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: That is why
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: That is why we are organizing a Tax Amazon Action Conference for January 25th.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: Please be there.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: This will be the first of our grassroots democratic conferences, and I believe, as a socialist, as a rank-and-file member of the labor movement, that all major decisions in our Tax Amazon movement should be made at mass grassroots conferences.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: We expect
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: We expect that at that first conference there will be lots to discuss, including different proposals on how much the tax should raise annually, what it should fund, and what tax mechanism we should use.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: In February, we need to organize our second grassroots tax Amazon conference, and I hope, and we hope, that at this conference we can take a vote on several of the different proposed options for the Amazon tax to agree on a broadly adopted proposal to file our ballot initiative.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: In my view,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: The tax should fund a major expansion of social housing for all the reasons that we have already stated, including funding some other aspects of a Green New Deal, such as supporting weatherization for the existing homes of working class homeowners.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: And you know, the problem we face is not a paucity of things that need to fund.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: In a city that is deeply unequal, with historic and unprecedented degrees of inequality, we're spoiled for choices.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: So much needs to be fully funded, from education to infrastructure.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: But we should be aware that the more things the initiative seeks to fund, the more complicated it becomes, and the more it becomes, as a union leader just recently said, becomes like a Christmas tree.

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: As hard fought as it will be is not the last step in our struggle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: We're going to go farther than that on the inspiration of having won something this year.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: So we should aim to have a clear message of what the tax is funding.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: I think we should consider a tax that would raise at least $200 to $500 million annually with no sunset clause.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: You know, despite the setback of the repeal in 2018, our movement to tax Amazon in 2018 was so inspiring that there were movements in other cities to do the same, to tax big tech and other big corporations.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: And that same year, despite the repeal, San Francisco won a ballot initiative that taxes big tech to the tune of $300 million.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: If the working people of San Francisco can do it, so can we.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: As for the mechanism of the big business tax, we have some options.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: We have not too many options, but we have the employee hours tax, a payroll tax.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: I've asked the city staff to do more research on this that will be shared with the movement.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: But to be clear, no matter which mechanism we pick, it will be a tax only on big business.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: We call it the Amazon tax because we want to be crystal clear.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: This is not a tax on small businesses.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: It is not a tax on workers.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: It is not a tax on jobs.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: It is not a tax on renters.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: It is not a tax on homeowners.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: It is only a tax on our city's wealthiest businesses.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: Seattle's crisis of inequality is not ours alone.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: There is a crisis, as we know, in every city in the United States and all around the world.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: As a socialist, I believe that this dysfunction is built into the system of capitalism.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: We are told, under capitalism, we are told it is impossible to have decent standards of living for most of us, that corporations' endless quest for profits have to be prioritized over housing, healthcare, education, and a livable planet for all.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: That strong rent control, living wages, and Medicare for all are impossible.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: It is a can't do message.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: It says something about their system, the bosses and the billionaire system, the system of capitalism, that such basic things as housing and health care in the 21st century are being denied to working people and that instead we are being taken down the road to climate catastrophe.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: The system
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: was not built for us, it was not built for human needs, it was not built to be environmentally sustainable.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.text: That's why I'm a socialist, because I believe we need a socialist world.

segments.text: And when you understand that it's linked to the nature of capitalism, it suddenly makes sense.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_07
